In this proclamation, President Donald J. Trump declares February 2018 as American Heart Month. He highlights the importance of raising awareness about the risk factors, warning signs, and symptoms associated with heart disease, which is the leading cause of death in the United States. The proclamation emphasizes the advancements in medical procedures and treatments for heart conditions, as well as the understanding of risk factors such as high blood pressure, high cholesterol, and type 2 diabetes. The President encourages Americans to take preventative measures, including maintaining a healthy lifestyle and not smoking, to reduce the likelihood of developing heart disease. He also honors those who have lost their lives to heart disease and recognizes healthcare providers and researchers working towards its prevention and treatment. The proclamation concludes by urging Americans to participate in National Wear Red Day on February 2, 2018, as a symbol of their commitment to fighting heart disease.